                        <p> <hi rend="initialcap">C</hi>ASE 7.—<name type="person">Private Harrison Tibbetts</name>, <name type="organization">Co. A, 12th Mass.</name>; age 24; was admitted <date type="admit" when="1862-06-01">June 1, 1862</date>, with chronic diarrhœa.  He recovered and was acting as wardmaster when, on <date type="injury" when="1862-10-11">October 11</date>, be was attacked with diphtheria, which proved fatal on <date type="death" when="1862-10-19">the 19th</date>.  <hi rend="italic">Post-mortem</hi> examination: The pharynx,
                                        tonsils and velum palati were covered with false membrane
                                        and the larynx was lined throughout with the characteristic
                                        exudation. On the left side of the lower part of the larynx
                                        was an abscess containing about three ounces of offensive
                                        pus. The parotid glands were much enlarged and the
                                        surrounding cellular tissue œdematous.—<hi rend="italic">Hospital, <name type="place">Alexandria, Va.</name></hi> </p>                        
